    <!-- Add insight / key takeaway directly related to activity / learner experience -->
     <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Suggested Time</title>
                    <p>10 minutes</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Objective</title>
                    <p>To formalize the core theorems governing cyclic quadrilaterals based on data gathered during the anchor activity.</p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Key Takeaways &amp; Teacher Connection</title>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p><alert>Connecting to Learner Work:</alert> Collect total sums calculated by different groups. Standardize the discovery: A quadrilateral is <alert>cyclic</alert> if and only if all four vertices touch a single circle circumference. The opposite interior angles are supplementary, meaning they add up to exactly <m>180^\circ</m>.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p><alert>Exterior Angle Property:</alert> Because angles on a straight line add to <m>180^\circ</m>, extending a side creates a direct relationship: The exterior angle of a cyclic quadrilateral is always equal to its interior opposite angle.</p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

    <insight>
        <title>Key Insight: The Cyclical Balance</title>
        <p>When working with a <alert>cyclic quadrilateral</alert>, think of it as an algebraic seesaw balanced at <m>180^\circ</m>. If one interior angle increases, the angle directly across the circle must decrease by that exact same amount. Furthermore, look for lines extended outside the circle; the <alert>exterior angle</alert> acts as a perfect geometric clone of the <alert>interior opposite angle</alert>.</p>
        <figure xml:id="fig-cyclic-quad-insight">
            <caption>Opposite angles in cyclic quadrilateral ABCD sum to 180 degrees, and the exterior angle at vertex B equals the opposite interior angle at vertex D.</caption>
            <image source="images/cyclic-quadrilateral-properties.png" width="80%">
                <description>A circle containing a four-sided polygon ABCD where all vertices touch the circumference. Opposite angles A and C are highlighted in one color, while B and D are highlighted in another. Line AB is extended to point E, showing that exterior angle CBE matches interior angle ADC.</description>
            </image>
        </figure>
    </insight>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

